<h3 id="account-btc-address-change">Can the digital currency deposit addresses associated with my account expire?</h3>

<p>Yes, so you should always check before sending a deposit to make sure you're sending funds to a good address. We're not responsible for funds sent to an expired address. You are allowed 5 addresses for each currency before any start to expire. So if you don't create more than 5 addresses, none will expire. But once you create 6 or more addresses, one or more addresses will be automatically set to expire. If an address is set to expire, it will be clearly marked - the address will have the status "expiring #" where # = number of days remaining (starting from 7) before it expires. We recommend that you stop using an address that is set to expire as soon as possible. You can't choose which of the addresses is set to expire but we plan to offer this option later. An address just marked as "Used" is OK to deposit to so long as there's no indication it's set to expire.</p>

<h3 id="direct-mining-payouts">Is it OK to send my mining payouts directly to my deposit address?</h3>

<p>Only if you're very careful not to send to an expired or expiring address (see above). If you want to send mining payouts directly to a deposit address, make sure you don't create any more than 5 deposit addresses, since after that they can expire.</p>

<h3 id="what-is-bitcoin">What is Bitcoin (XBT)? What are math-based currencies?</h3>

<p>Bitcoin (XBT) is an electronic currency that is "decentralized", meaning that it isn't controlled by the central authority of any government or organization. Instead, Bitcoin is controlled by mathematical algorithms implemented in cryptographic computer technology over a highly distributed network. The essential upshot of this decentralized mathematical control is that Bitcoin works according to fixed rules that cannot be changed by any central authority.</p>

<p>Bitcoins can be stored securely while remaining completely under their owner's control (i.e. without the need for a bank). They can be transferred quickly, cheaply and securely. Transactions are non-reversible, like cash transactions - there's no such thing as a stop payment or a chargeback. And there's a finite limit to the number of bitcoins that will eventually be created, which means Bitcoin is a deflationary currency, and is therefore expected to increase, rather than decrease, in value.</p>

<p>Bitcoins are stored in "wallets" containing a public and private key. The public key is shared for transactions, but the private key must be kept secure, since theft of this information amounts to theft of all coins in the wallet.</p>

<p>Bitcoin is one of a class of currencies that utilize cryptography, called "crypto-currencies" or "math-based currencies." Bitcoin is the first popular math-based currency, but a few others are emerging, such as XRP (the currency for paying Ripple transaction fees) and Litecoin (LTC).</p>

<p>What does Bitcoin mean for the trader or investor? While Bitcoin has seen periods of relative stability, it has for the most part been quite volatile, making it excellent for active trading. It has also proved so far to be an excellent (though highly speculative) long-term investment. Some alternative math-based currencies such as XRP and LTC have also seen volatility and appreciation in value. But past performance, of course, is no guarantee of future results.</p>

<p>There's much more to learn about Bitcoin. One place to start is here: <a
    href="https://www.weusecoins.com/en/">https://www.weusecoins.com/en/</a></p>

<h3 id="what-is-ven">What is Ven (XVN)?</h3>

<p>Ven (XVN) is the only digital currency that's completely back by assets (a basket of currencies, commodities, and carbon futures). Ven was created in 2007 within the <a
    href="http://www.hubculture.com/">Hub Culture</a> social network. Ven is easy to use - transactions are instantaneous, available to anyone with an email address, and free inside the network. Since it's backed by commodities and carbon futures, Ven is environmentally friendly and more moderately inflationary than traditional national currencies. Ven is controlled and managed by the Hub Culture social network. Oversight of reserves is managed in conjunction with partner banks, including <a
    href="http://www.hsbc.com/">HSBC</a>. Thousands of people and organizations use Ven through the <a
    href="http://www.hubculture.com/">Hub Culture</a> stores, supplier relationships, micro-payments, and other activities. API protocols mean Ven can be exchanged anywhere for anything.
</p>

