<h3 id="market-price-protection">My market orders are cancelled - what is market price protection?</h3>

<p>Market price protection cancels a market order if it tries to fill at a price that goes against you too much. It means you shouldn't be using market orders because the volume on the exchange is too low. You should stick with limit orders so you control the price you get. Market orders can have a lot of price slippage when the volume is low and you end up buying at a really high price or selling at a really low price. The market price protection mechanism protects you from this danger.</p>

<h3 id="reversed-pairs">Why are some currency pairs on Kraken "reversed" compared to other exchanges?</h3>

<p>It's industry standard in Forex currency markets to offer the higher valued pair for any two currencies. That is, given the choice between pair x/y or y/x, it's industry standard to offer the higher valued pair. While we don't adhere to this standard strictly, we do generally avoid low valued pairs because they create many problems for trading. To illustrate the problems, we'll consider dogecoin (XDG) and bitcoin (XBT). To simplify the math, we'll assume that XDG/XBT market price is 0.00000100 (it wasn't too far from this at the time of writing - less than 0.00000120). Here are the problems created by offering such a low valued pair on an exchange:</p>
<ol>
  <li><b>Higher trading costs:</b> Most exchanges offer at most 8 decimal place precision for placing trades. This means that for trading XDG/XBT, you can at best only place trades with an accuracy of 1% relative to market price (0.00000001 = 1% of 0.00000100). And this means that every time XDG/XBT is traded, price will slip at least 1%. If you're on the wrong end of the price slip, you effectively have an extra cost of 1% in the trade. Given our current trade fee (0.2%), that's 5 times more than the trade fee!
  </li>
  <li><b>Inhibits volume/liquidity:</b> Volume and liquidity on an exchange is inhibited when traders can't set prices with fine-grained accuracy. As noted above, traders of XDG/XBT can't set prices with accuracy - at best an accuracy of 1% of market price. For a similar comparison, imagine if an exchange only allowed traders to set prices for XBT/USD in increments of $5. Volume and liquidity would be inhibited and traders would understandably be quite annoyed about it. We think traders should be similarly annoyed with exchanges that offer the XDG/XBT pair at such a low price.
  </li>
  <li><b>Inhibits price discovery:</b> Again, since traders can only set price with an accuracy of 1%, the market for XDG/XBT cannot discover true market price very accurately.
  </li>
</ol>

<p>All these problems go away if the pair XBT/XDG is used, which is why we use this pair instead. Some pairs we avoid, such as LTC/XBT, aren't currently valued nearly as low as XDG/XBT, but we avoid them anyway since there's always the chance they could drop a lot more in the future. While we choose the best pairs for trading, we understand that the reversed pairs make it awkward to compare with other exchanges. To solve this difficulty, we're looking at developing a 1/x view so the inverted pairs can easily be compared to other exchanges (but no estimate on when this feature might be available yet).</p>

