<h3 id="account-security">What can I do to make my Kraken account secure?</h3>

<p>
  The full list of security measures we recommend for users is described in the <a
    href="/security/practices">Security Practices</a> section (under "Your Security Practices"). Here's a summary of the more important points:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>Set up <a
      href="#what-is-tfa">two-factor authentication</a> for your Kraken account login. Two-factor authentication should also be set up for the email associated with your Kraken account.
  </li>
  <li>Create a <a
      href="#master-key">master key</a> for your account. Without a master key, your Kraken account is no more secure than your email account. Creating a master key provides an extra layer of protection between your email account and your Kraken account (someone who gained access to your email account would still have a hard time gaining access to your Kraken account unless they also had the master key).
  </li>
  <li>To really lock down your account, you may also want to set up two-factor authentication for withdrawals and lock your settings with the <a
      href="#global-settings-lock">global settings lock</a>.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="security-personal-info">What does Kraken do to secure my personal information?</h3>

<p>The privacy of our user's personal information is very important to us and we've protected this information through the dedicated design efforts of the highly professional security experts on our team. Of course, we can't be very specific since it undermines security to give too many details, but here's a brief summary:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Databases containing sensitive user data aren't accessible from our site. They're encrypted and can't be decrypted without access to multiple highly secured systems.</li>
  <li>By far the most likely scenario for leakage of personal data would be user-specific, rather than a breach of the database as a whole - that is, if someone gained access to your personal login credentials, and could then see the same personal information you can see when you log into your account. But we provide many <a
      href="#account-security">security tools</a> to help you secure your account. At minimum, you should have <a
      href="#what-is-tfa">two-factor authentication</a> for account login and create a <a
      href="#master-key">master key</a>. But you may also want create a <a
      href="#global-settings-lock">global settings lock</a> on your account, since doing so hides the most sensitive information in your account, such as your document scans.
  </li>
</ul>

<p>For more information, see our <a href="/security/practices">Security Practices</a> section.</p>

<h3 id="full-reserves">Does Kraken hold full reserves?</h3>

<p>Yes. And and we've developed a state of the art audit process in order to prove to third parties, including our customers, that customer funds are properly held. See <a
    href="/security/audit">here</a> for more information on our audit process.</p>

<h3 id="security-image">What is the monster cartoon on the login page?</h3>

<p>It's a security image used to help Kraken users recognize that they're on the official Kraken website, and not a phishing website that may be attempting to harvest their login credentials.</p>

<p>The security image shown to you is unique and is dynamically generated based on your IP address. It cannot be displayed on other (potentially malicious) websites.</p>

<p>If you don't recognize the displayed image, the following are possible causes:</p>
<ul>
  <li>It's your very first visit to the Kraken website. Welcome!</li>
  <li>Your IP address has changed since your last visit.</li>
  <li>The Kraken website has changed the way it generates security images. We'll let you know if this happens.</li>
  <li>You forgot what your monster looks like. Take a moment to get to know it better.</li>
  <li>You may be on a phishing site that is attempting to steal your login credentials.</li>
</ul>

<p>When logging in to Kraken, <strong>always ensure that your browser URL is set to www.kraken.com</strong>. If you think you've discovered a Kraken phishing website, please <a
    href="https://support.kraken.com">contact support</a> immediately.</p>

<p>The security image generation is based on the <a
    href="http://www.splitbrain.org/projects/monsterid">MonsterID method</a>.</p>

<h3 id="what-is-tfa">What is two-factor authentication?</h3>

<p>Two-factor authentication is an enhanced security measure requiring a second passcode in addition to username and password. See <a
    href="/security/practices#two-factor-authentication">Two-Factor Authentication</a> (in the "Security Practices" section) for details.
</p>

<h3 id="tfa-available">Sounds great! Do you offer two-factor authentication?</h3>

<p>Of course! You can set up two-factor authentication for account login, deposits, withdrawals, ordering and API actions under the <a
    href="/u/security?tab=tfa">security tab</a> on your account screen. And you probably should.</p>

<h3 id="master-key">What is the "master key" shown on the two-factor authentication page?</h3>

<p>The <a
    href="/u/security?tab=tfa">master key</a> is a special passcode reserved for certain sensitive account actions that won't need to be performed very often. For best security, we highly recommend that you create the master key. But it should be kept very secure and separate from your other passcodes. Creating the master key does the following:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>Increases the security of account password reset (the master key must be provided for reset).</li>
  <li>Increases the security of two-factor bypass for account login (the master key must be provided to get a temporary OTP bypass code).</li>
  <li>Allows to you bypass the <a
      href="#global-settings-lock">global settings lock</a> so that settings can be changed immediately.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="what-is-pgp">What is PGP encryption?</h3>

<p>PGP (Pretty Good Privacy) is a public key encryption program that has become the most popular standard for email encryption. (The "pretty good" bit is meant to be a bit of an ironic understatement.) In addition to encrypting and decrypting email, PGP is used to sign messages so that the receiver can verify both the identity of the sender and the integrity of the content. PGP uses a private key that must be kept secret and a public key that sender and receiver must share.</p>

<p>Kraken uses one public key for automated outgoing mail sent to users and another key for correspondence between users and Kraken support staff. For more information, see <a
    href="/security/practices#pgp-gpg-encryption">PGP/GPG Encryption</a> (in the "Security Practices" section).</p>

<h3 id="submit-pgp-pub-key">How do I tell Kraken what my public PGP key is?</h3>

<p>Under <a
    href="/u/settings/account">Settings</a> on your account screen you'll find a field for entering your PGP public key.
</p>

<h3 id="site-outgoing-pgp-pub-key">Where can I find the PGP key to verify automated outgoing email from Kraken?</h3>

<p>Our key for verifying the authenticity of automated outgoing email from our site is under <a
    href="/security/pgp">PGP Public Key</a> (in the "Security" section).</p>

<h3 id="site-incoming-pgp-pub-key">Where can I find the PGP key for correspondence with Kraken support staff?</h3>

<p>We're working on it - check back soon.</p>

<h3 id="what-is-a-pgp-signature">What is the file "signature.asc" attached to email I receive from Kraken?</h3>

<p>This is a PGP signature that can be used to verify the authenticity of the email and help prove that Kraken is the author of the email. It's generated using both the content of the email and the secret Kraken PGP key. You can verify the signature of each email using PGP and the <a
    href="/security/pgp">public Kraken PGP key</a>.</p>

<h3 id="session-invalid">Why am I getting a "Session Invalid" message?</h3>

<p>If you receive a "Session Invalid" message, it's probably something harmless. Your system may have changed its IP address for legitimate reasons during your login session. This might happen, for example, if your computer goes to sleep while you are logged in. However, you've been logged out as a precaution because a change occurred that might indicate that an attacker is trying to hijack your session. Session hijacking is a process whereby an attacker attempts to take over a pre-authenticated connection. We recommend you run a virus scanner in order to ensure that your system isn't compromised. If you're using an insecure public network, we recommend moving to a secure network. If you continue to get the "Session Invalid" message, discovering the problem will probably require that you contact your internet provider, and the companies who created your browser and operating system. It's probably not an issue that we can help you with.</p>

<h3 id="global-settings-lock">What is the "Global Settings Lock"?</h3>

<p>The <a
    href="/u/settings/account">Global Settings Lock</a> is an enhanced security feature that helps prevent tampering of your account information by an attacker that has gained access to your account. When enabled, the following account information is locked and cannot be immediately changed:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>Account settings</li>
  <li>Password</li>
  <li>Notifications</li>
  <li>Withdrawal addresses</li>
  <li>Verification information (also hidden)</li>
  <li>Two-factor authentication (also hidden)</li>
  <li>API keys (also hidden)</li>
</ul>

<p>The settings lock also hides certain sensitive information in your account. Your verification information won't be visible. If you've created API keys, they won't be visible. And setup information for two-factor authentication won't be visible (i.e. the setup keys and QR codes for Google Authenticator).</p>

<p>Once the lock is turned on, settings can't be changed until an unlock request takes effect. The unlock request can take effect up to 30 days after the unlock request is made (the number of days is user-specifiable). If 0 is entered for the number of days to unlock, a <a
    href="#master-key">master key</a> will be required to unlock the settings (the master key should be created first). An email notification is immediately sent whenever an unlock request is made.
</p>

<p>Suppose, for example, that you turn on the settings lock with the unlock process set to take seven days. Then someone gains access to your account and tries to change your settings (say they want to change your Bitcoin withdrawal address so they can withdraw your coins to their address). You would receive immediate email notification of the unlock request, and would have 7 days to stop the request before it took effect. When you discovered the unauthorized unlock request, you would contact our <a
    href="https://support.kraken.com">support staff</a> right away so we could take the necessary steps to protect your account.
</p>

<p>It's possible to use the <a
    href="#master-key">master key</a> feature to override the lock (and thus unlock settings immediately), provided that you create the master key prior to locking. If the number of days to unlock is set to 0, then the master key will be required to unlock the settings (not just required to override the waiting period). This override option can be very convenient, but remember that the security benefit of the settings lock feature will only be good to the extent that your master key is kept safe. If someone gains access to both your account and the master key, the settings lock won't slow them down.
</p></div>
